{
  "text": "Image acquisition using integrating mode with DE-12. Chargecoupled device (CCD) cameras are widely used despite their relatively low signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) at medium to high spatial frequencies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . More recently, the development of radiation-hardened complementary metal-oxide semiconductor (CMOS) detectors that can directly detect primary electrons in an electron microscope has proven a superior alternative to CCD cameras. These new direct detectors have been successfully used for data collection in cryo-EM (for example, see refs 2,3,11,12) . In addition to improving the spectral SNR (SSNR) of acquired images [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , direct detection cameras also provide the advantage of intrinsic dose fractionation by recording multiple images per specimen area within a single continuous exposure (hereafter we refer to this type of data collection as a 'movie' and each individual image within the movie a 'frame'). Frames can be prepared individually or in groups before being used for image reconstruction [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "594690",
